1
00:00:00,660 --> 00:00:01,820
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:02,540 --> 00:00:06,060
Happy New Year 2017.

3
00:00:06,640 --> 00:00:10,400
Wishing you the fulfillment of your plans and all the best in the new year.

4
00:00:11,640 --> 00:00:21,280
I want to share some info gifts that you'll find on my Yandex.Disk in the folder "My schemes from videos for YouTube".

5
00:00:21,280 --> 00:00:33,440
The first is a diagram of our resonator with the inductor, showing the layer-by-layer winding scheme and wire lengths.

6
00:00:33,960 --> 00:00:40,520
The drawing was done by Muslim Afandiev from Azerbaijan — big thanks to him.

7
00:00:42,220 --> 00:00:49,460
The second is this table provided by Sergey Fyodorov, known on YouTube as Fedor 001.

8
00:00:50,760 --> 00:00:53,700
It's a table of isotopes with frequencies.

9
00:00:53,700 --> 00:01:06,700
I want to draw your attention to hydrogen-3 and its frequency in MHz, and aluminum-27 and its frequency in kHz — 1506.

10
00:01:07,260 --> 00:01:10,280
We see a practical multiple of these frequencies.

11
00:01:11,320 --> 00:01:25,460
This table leads to understanding why we need to use aluminum specifically on the antenna, and what atoms it excites in the surrounding space during Tesla coil operation.

12
00:01:25,740 --> 00:01:29,240
You can also tune to other frequencies.

13
00:01:30,340 --> 00:01:30,920
Here you can see.

14
00:01:32,360 --> 00:01:36,100
Well, a good frequency for us is nitrogen-14.

15
00:01:37,020 --> 00:01:40,580
It also has a multiple with an aluminum antenna.

16
00:01:41,400 --> 00:01:46,000
Both hydrogen and nitrogen are present in air.

17
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:51,260
And their presence plays a key role in how our device works.

18
00:01:52,720 --> 00:02:00,720
The third is a book called "Electricity and its unusual properties" by Oleg Vasiliev.

19
00:02:01,420 --> 00:02:06,240
The book is written in an accessible form, in simple language.

20
00:02:06,680 --> 00:02:14,380
In it you'll find info about the existence of a second particle responsible for electric charge.

21
00:02:14,380 --> 00:02:19,000
About its new properties compared to the electron.

22
00:02:19,560 --> 00:02:30,500
And about how this particle manifests in the devices we assemble trying to achieve an over-unity effect.

23
00:02:30,640 --> 00:02:37,500
And also about how this particle manifests in nature, in the surrounding environment, and what phenomena it leads to.

24
00:02:37,880 --> 00:02:39,280
Recommend reading it.

25
00:02:40,420 --> 00:02:47,240
And the fourth is the book "Nikola Tesla's Patents" published in Russian.

26
00:02:47,980 --> 00:02:55,620
In this collection you'll find original images from Tesla's patents and their descriptions.

27
00:02:56,740 --> 00:03:05,280
Pay special attention to section four of this book — "Devices working with high-frequency sources and circuit controllers".

28
00:03:05,280 --> 00:03:14,600
In this section, Tesla's thought process about how to create pulse duration in a system is clearly visible.

29
00:03:15,060 --> 00:03:17,960
For this he used mechanical controllers.

30
00:03:18,860 --> 00:03:22,740
That doesn't mean these controllers have to be mechanical.

31
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:30,900
It's enough to understand his idea and transfer the principle to a modern element base.

32
00:03:31,900 --> 00:03:37,940
Once you've studied this material, you'll discover a lot of images you've seen online.

33
00:03:38,620 --> 00:03:46,260
Images were pulled out of Tesla's patents and interpreted freely, which led to information distortion.

34
00:03:47,660 --> 00:04:01,240
Tesla himself worked with high-potential currents and used controlled spark gaps specifically, and he always clearly indicated the presence of LC resonance or wave processes in the system.

35
00:04:02,600 --> 00:04:10,500
If maximum electric potential was needed in the system specifically, then he was talking about LC resonance.

36
00:04:11,380 --> 00:04:26,720
And if wave processes were involved, then Tesla clearly indicated that the wire length in the system had to be exactly equal to a quarter wavelength of the electromagnetic disturbance in the system.

37
00:04:27,760 --> 00:04:36,860
You have to understand that plasma behavior in a magnetic field is analogous to the behavior of a conductor through which current flows.

38
00:04:37,240 --> 00:04:46,460
If the conductor is movable, it'll inevitably be pushed out of the magnetic field depending on how current flows through it.

39
00:04:46,460 --> 00:04:50,280
Electromagnetic motors are made on this principle.

40
00:04:51,200 --> 00:05:06,900
Applied in a system where magnetic discharge quenching or interruption is done, plasma becomes a kind of mobile conductor that oscillates in the magnetic field.

41
00:05:07,440 --> 00:05:15,760
But to run such experiments you'll need a pretty powerful power source with high potential.

42
00:05:15,760 --> 00:05:21,680
I want to dedicate this video to building that power source.

43
00:05:23,500 --> 00:05:25,680
Its dimensions are quite compact.

44
00:05:26,760 --> 00:05:40,860
And the main distinctive feature of this source is that it can deliver powerful current movement at high potential, which is very important for magnetic spark gap operation.

45
00:05:40,860 --> 00:05:46,000
In this video I'll go step by step on how to build this unit.

46
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:54,000
So, we'll build a high-voltage DC lab unit according to the schematic shown here.

47
00:05:54,480 --> 00:06:04,220
This schematic, like all my other schematics from the videos, will be on my Yandex.Disk for free access at the address you know.

48
00:06:04,840 --> 00:06:06,960
Let's go through the circuit solutions.

49
00:06:07,960 --> 00:06:15,840
All the components in the schematic are available in most electronics stores and easy to buy.

50
00:06:16,620 --> 00:06:28,300
The driving generator of the circuit is built on a TL494 chip that works in two-cycle mode with pauses between control pulses.

51
00:06:28,300 --> 00:06:39,020
There's the option to regulate duty cycle, which in turn determines the final power and voltage at the output under load.

52
00:06:39,320 --> 00:06:41,880
And the option to regulate frequency.

53
00:06:42,300 --> 00:06:54,560
The frequency will be set once — to whatever best suits the ferrite core of the high-voltage pulse transformer.

54
00:06:55,560 --> 00:07:02,820
There's also a switch that disables chip generation.

55
00:07:03,420 --> 00:07:16,600
This is for convenience — when the circuit is connected, you don't need to power everything else off; just disabling generation stops the high-voltage at the output.

56
00:07:16,600 --> 00:07:36,100
Then control pulses, through 10 Ω limiting resistors, reach two identical TC4420 drivers, which in turn drive the gates through 8.2 Ω damping resistors.

57
00:07:36,100 --> 00:07:55,580
The IRF3205E keys work on the primary winding of the pulse transformer, converting the input DC voltage of 12–36 V into high-voltage pulses on the secondary winding,

58
00:07:56,120 --> 00:08:03,200
which is then rectified using four diode columns and applied to the load.

59
00:08:03,200 --> 00:08:09,060
The diode columns in their schematic form a high-voltage diode bridge.

60
00:08:11,020 --> 00:08:22,500
This two-cycle converter scheme is called push-pull and is the best circuit solution at inverter supply voltages up to 100 V.

61
00:08:22,500 --> 00:08:25,120
Now let's go through the schematic block by block.

62
00:08:26,480 --> 00:08:40,640
For mounting the logic control side we'll need a 5×5 cm prototyping board with single-sided contacts.

63
00:08:41,640 --> 00:08:52,440
Mounting is done with wire-wrap — that is, we form the traces with wires.

64
00:08:53,620 --> 00:08:56,480
Here's what it looks like ready.

65
00:08:56,680 --> 00:08:58,120
What do we see here?

66
00:08:58,400 --> 00:08:59,480
The main elements.

67
00:08:59,940 --> 00:09:03,560
Two TC4420 drivers.

68
00:09:04,080 --> 00:09:08,520
Next, the TL494 driving chip.

69
00:09:09,200 --> 00:09:11,580
Power input terminal.

70
00:09:12,440 --> 00:09:17,520
Switch for disabling the driving generator.

71
00:09:18,820 --> 00:09:26,080
50 kΩ trim pot, responsible for the circuit's frequency.

72
00:09:26,640 --> 00:09:34,320
And the main variable resistor responsible for duty cycle.

73
00:09:35,020 --> 00:09:38,480
Its value is 10 kΩ.

74
00:09:38,480 --> 00:09:45,340
You can also see leads marked minus and plus on the schematic.

75
00:09:46,760 --> 00:09:58,700
These are two outputs that connect to a cooler motor that'll cool the transistor heat sink.

76
00:09:58,700 --> 00:10:06,200
12 V comes out after this L7812 regulator.

77
00:10:07,520 --> 00:10:08,560
Here's how it looks.

78
00:10:09,160 --> 00:10:17,160
The regulator's heat sink is made from cable clamps.

79
00:10:17,340 --> 00:10:18,200
Recommended.

80
00:10:18,420 --> 00:10:22,080
Very handy, easy to work with.

81
00:10:22,240 --> 00:10:24,860
Has a flat surface and gets installed.

82
00:10:24,860 --> 00:10:33,840
These heat sinks can also be mounted on the surfaces of loaded drivers for extra cooling.

83
00:10:36,440 --> 00:10:41,340
Let's place our control block here.

84
00:10:44,120 --> 00:10:48,240
You can see the cooling fan.

85
00:10:48,560 --> 00:10:52,780
It's rated 12 V, 0.1 A.

86
00:10:54,640 --> 00:10:56,800
Place it here in its spot.

87
00:10:57,960 --> 00:11:05,680
This regulator is needed so the cooler runs at 12 V.

88
00:11:05,740 --> 00:11:14,680
That's what it's designed for, because the whole logic side is powered from a higher potential.

89
00:11:14,680 --> 00:11:22,080
If the supply is higher than 12 V, this DC-DC converter is set at 15 V.

90
00:11:23,200 --> 00:11:28,480
The DC-DC converter is built on an LM2596 chip.

91
00:11:29,100 --> 00:11:32,900
You can build it yourself, or buy one.

92
00:11:32,960 --> 00:11:38,220
They're also off-the-shelf items.

93
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:45,300
This trim pot sets the output voltage.

94
00:11:45,760 --> 00:11:49,060
Output comes from the OUT terminals — plus and minus.

95
00:11:49,480 --> 00:11:54,600
Input is the IN terminals — plus and minus.

96
00:11:55,880 --> 00:11:59,020
Placed here at this point.

97
00:11:59,020 --> 00:12:08,240
On the schematic you can see the main reservoir electrolytic cap, 4700 µF, 50 V.

98
00:12:08,840 --> 00:12:11,380
It has these overall dimensions.

99
00:12:12,520 --> 00:12:14,080
And here are its ratings.

100
00:12:15,500 --> 00:12:18,260
Place it in its spot.

101
00:12:19,160 --> 00:12:26,140
Note that the plus supply voltage goes through a thermostat.

102
00:12:27,180 --> 00:12:33,920
The thermostat has a max current of 10 A and a trip point of 70 degrees.

103
00:12:33,920 --> 00:12:48,260
Thermostats are sold in these housings — they keep the circuit closed until the temperature is exceeded, which I noted schematically.

104
00:12:48,800 --> 00:12:57,380
Most likely there's a bimetallic strip in the thermostat housing that bends under temperature and opens the contacts.

105
00:12:59,260 --> 00:13:01,900
This module sits here.

106
00:13:02,500 --> 00:13:16,600
Next we'll need terminals to easily attach the output of the high-voltage wires that'll later feed the load.

107
00:13:17,820 --> 00:13:22,140
Terminals are marked in different colors so we don't mix them up.

108
00:13:22,300 --> 00:13:25,800
Plus and minus.

109
00:13:27,400 --> 00:13:31,960
Next, the main element — the core.

110
00:13:32,780 --> 00:13:41,700
The core for a powerful pulse transformer should have large geometric dimensions.

111
00:13:41,700 --> 00:13:50,820
You can use cores from line transformers (TVS), or equivalently combine two TVS cores.

112
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:57,180
TVS is the line transformer from old TVs.

113
00:13:57,180 --> 00:14:02,640
The core geometric dimensions we'll be using — I'll show now.

114
00:14:02,920 --> 00:14:12,740
So it has dimensions of 6.5 cm by 6.5 cm.

115
00:14:12,740 --> 00:14:20,600
Wire-magnet width 2.8 cm.

116
00:14:21,860 --> 00:14:26,980
The central pillar is wider than the side ones.

117
00:14:28,080 --> 00:14:33,260
Width 2 cm and 2.8 cm respectively.

118
00:14:33,260 --> 00:14:42,080
We'll wind our high-voltage transformer on this 2000 nm permeability core.

119
00:14:42,260 --> 00:14:44,320
This part goes here.

120
00:14:45,180 --> 00:14:50,520
Next we'll look at our diode columns.

121
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:56,540
They're marked on the schematic — we looked at them.

122
00:14:57,660 --> 00:15:04,100
Each diode column is designed to handle voltage up to 10,000 V.

123
00:15:04,100 --> 00:15:09,860
HER508 diodes are bought for this.

124
00:15:10,760 --> 00:15:16,660
Each diode of this brand is rated up to 1000 V.

125
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:24,860
As a result, with 10 of them in series, we get a diode column rated 10 kV.

126
00:15:25,860 --> 00:15:28,520
Ready diode column.

127
00:15:28,800 --> 00:15:29,860
Looks like this.

128
00:15:29,960 --> 00:15:33,740
You need to make 4 of them total.

129
00:15:34,820 --> 00:15:36,020
How I made them.

130
00:15:36,560 --> 00:15:38,260
Connected in series.

131
00:15:38,880 --> 00:15:43,460
The housing is made of cable channel.

132
00:15:44,460 --> 00:15:47,380
Let me show the cable channel.

133
00:15:48,060 --> 00:15:48,600
Here it is.

134
00:15:50,760 --> 00:15:54,420
A piece of cable channel with these dimensions.

135
00:15:56,000 --> 00:15:59,940
1 cm by 12 mm.

136
00:16:00,680 --> 00:16:12,900
For solid mounting we drill a hole every centimeter, opposite each other, with about 10 mm spacing.

137
00:16:13,460 --> 00:16:19,540
After which the diodes are laid in here.

138
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:22,960
And then the plate is closed.

139
00:16:24,640 --> 00:16:28,020
After this we solder it reliably.

140
00:16:29,860 --> 00:16:39,720
I don't recommend cutting the leads, because they'll provide some cooling for the diodes inside.

141
00:16:39,720 --> 00:16:47,800
You also need to leave free holes for air passage.

142
00:16:48,080 --> 00:16:50,300
You get a build like this.

143
00:16:52,960 --> 00:16:57,720
Next, the main part — the power module.

144
00:16:57,720 --> 00:17:15,520
The power module is mounted on a heat sink about 8 by 6.5 cm with a heat sink depth up to 3 cm.

145
00:17:16,180 --> 00:17:23,960
That's enough for two power switches to run with a cooling fan blowing.

146
00:17:24,960 --> 00:17:26,880
What do we see here?

147
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:35,450
Our thermal sensor fixed with two M3 screws, and two power transistors.

148
00:17:35,760 --> 00:17:38,880
Fixed with similar screws.

149
00:17:39,960 --> 00:17:48,280
Fixed with a bolt and a plastic insulator washer.

150
00:17:48,280 --> 00:17:54,600
Plastic insulators are also sold at electronics stores.

151
00:17:56,320 --> 00:18:04,380
They have a stud that goes into the hole of this transistor.

152
00:18:06,420 --> 00:18:17,700
You can also see the transistors are mounted directly on the heat sink, with a dielectric pad between them.

153
00:18:18,280 --> 00:18:33,870
The dielectric pad blocks current from passing through the cooling pad of the transistor, which is also pin 2 — the drain.

154
00:18:34,300 --> 00:18:39,730
So its presence is mandatory, otherwise you'd have a short circuit.

155
00:18:39,730 --> 00:18:45,970
I recommend making the dielectric pad from mica plates.

156
00:18:46,650 --> 00:18:58,470
You can buy them at the same stores, or disassemble old mica high-voltage capacitors, or buy a modern pad.

157
00:18:59,170 --> 00:19:05,050
Its characteristics are slightly worse but still acceptable.

158
00:19:06,050 --> 00:19:16,090
You can also see diodes connected between source and drain.

159
00:19:16,310 --> 00:19:20,010
Diodes designed to damp back-EMF spikes.

160
00:19:20,270 --> 00:19:24,270
Here they are, two MUR-460 diodes.

161
00:19:26,150 --> 00:19:33,330
Counter-connected zener diodes on the gate capacitance.

162
00:19:33,330 --> 00:19:36,210
Here they are — 12 V zeners.

163
00:19:36,910 --> 00:19:41,360
And 1 kΩ discharge resistors.

164
00:19:42,350 --> 00:19:45,250
These resistors are also shown.

165
00:19:46,330 --> 00:19:53,830
For those working with an aluminum heat sink for the first time, I'll give a few tips.

166
00:19:54,390 --> 00:20:01,550
Aluminum is a viscous metal, so working with it requires care.

167
00:20:01,550 --> 00:20:13,910
Since the screw holes are small, it's easy to break the drill bit and have it firmly stuck in the aluminum body.

168
00:20:14,450 --> 00:20:18,870
The same can happen when cutting threads.

169
00:20:19,510 --> 00:20:24,510
Here's an M3 tap — you can see its geometric size.

170
00:20:25,510 --> 00:20:35,470
The drill and tap materials are very brittle, so breaking is highly likely.

171
00:20:35,570 --> 00:20:41,670
To prevent this, I'd suggest using WD-40.

172
00:20:42,470 --> 00:20:48,330
For convenience I glued a syringe needle here.

173
00:20:49,330 --> 00:21:04,830
When using the liquid, aluminum doesn't stick to the tap or drill surface — no jamming, and the aluminum slides over the conductor surface.

174
00:21:05,390 --> 00:21:12,510
That way you protect the cutting edges from sticking in the soft metal.

175
00:21:13,170 --> 00:21:13,910
Important.

176
00:21:14,910 --> 00:21:33,290
Also, before mounting the power switches and thermal sensor, you need to lubricate the cooling surfaces that adjoin the heat sinks — both between the pad and between the cooling plate — with KPT-brand thermal paste.

177
00:21:33,290 --> 00:21:37,010
Thermal paste.

178
00:21:38,310 --> 00:21:44,390
That's it for the main nuances of the power block.

179
00:21:44,750 --> 00:22:00,530
You can also see I used 90-degree brackets from a hardware store to mount this heat sink in the enclosure later.

180
00:22:02,210 --> 00:22:06,050
This part goes here.

181
00:22:08,210 --> 00:22:14,130
Let me set that aside — another point on the schematic to note.

182
00:22:15,130 --> 00:22:22,530
You can see I marked the power source's minus input with an asterisk.

183
00:22:23,390 --> 00:22:29,250
And the inverter's minus input with an asterisk too.

184
00:22:29,610 --> 00:22:53,310
Note that these points connect directly through a power cable with a cross-section equal to the supply wire cross-section — all the other points connect too, but for this one you need to pay special attention, same as for —

185
00:22:53,310 --> 00:23:04,290
the power wire that goes to the primary winding, with a good cross-section.

186
00:23:05,290 --> 00:23:18,450
After the main blocks are ready and we know the dimensions of the elements, we can pick an enclosure.

187
00:23:19,450 --> 00:23:39,450
I recommend going with plastic — if you use metal, you'll need plastic insulators so there's no shorting from the diode column leads relative to the high-voltage.

188
00:23:39,450 --> 00:23:40,170
High-voltage.

189
00:23:40,170 --> 00:23:54,550
The main large-size elements are the diode columns themselves, the power module, and the high-voltage transformer core.

190
00:23:54,550 --> 00:24:06,430
You can see I picked it so the heat sink and the transformer have roughly the same dimensions, about 6.5 cm.

191
00:24:07,250 --> 00:24:10,930
These are the main parts that determine the geometry.

192
00:24:10,930 --> 00:24:18,170
After that, I found a suitable enclosure.

193
00:24:18,570 --> 00:24:27,730
The enclosure is from an old charger that broke down.

194
00:24:27,730 --> 00:24:32,610
This is its top cover.

195
00:24:39,110 --> 00:24:46,570
The top cover will cover all the components later.

196
00:24:46,670 --> 00:24:51,310
This is our main working surface.

197
00:24:51,310 --> 00:25:02,870
I got lucky — the back cover had an output for a cooling fan, an already-made window.

198
00:25:03,430 --> 00:25:13,430
You can see I did some gluing so the whole system didn't sit loose in the grooves — it's clearly fixed.

199
00:25:13,430 --> 00:25:30,350
I also already glued in the frequency trim pot, made a hole for the supply wires for our 12–36 V per the schematic.

200
00:25:31,050 --> 00:25:41,550
Also made a hole in a convenient spot for operating the variable resistor responsible for the driving generator's duty cycle.

201
00:25:41,550 --> 00:25:46,010
And a hole for the switch that disables generation.

202
00:25:48,010 --> 00:25:59,190
You can also see the front cover is made of cardboard — two layers.

203
00:25:59,410 --> 00:26:04,130
I picked a matching color because there wasn't a front cover.

204
00:26:04,130 --> 00:26:15,410
If there hadn't been a back cover either, I'd have glued a back cover similarly and made a hole for the cooler.

205
00:26:15,730 --> 00:26:32,470
To start the geometric arrangement of the main modules in the enclosure, we need to mount the cooler — it'll determine the geometric placement of the power module.

206
00:26:32,470 --> 00:26:38,570
Mounted, next we move to installing the power module.

207
00:26:39,390 --> 00:26:52,970
Install it centered opposite the cooling fan and mark the mounting holes.

208
00:26:52,970 --> 00:27:03,010
These are the main spots on both sides where the fixing bolts will go.

209
00:27:04,150 --> 00:27:16,730
After this — I did it in advance — you can see these holes, threads were cut in them for the fixing bolts.

210
00:27:16,730 --> 00:27:22,450
And you can also see holes I drilled.

211
00:27:22,890 --> 00:27:30,910
The holes correspond to being directly under the heat sink.

212
00:27:31,170 --> 00:27:35,610
Here you can see they're under the heat sink.

213
00:27:36,130 --> 00:27:43,670
Air will be drawn into these holes, picking up heat from the heat sink.

214
00:27:43,670 --> 00:27:51,690
And the cooler then ejects that air out of the enclosure.

215
00:27:52,850 --> 00:27:55,610
Those are the first dimension-defining elements.

216
00:27:56,250 --> 00:28:02,230
The second dimension-defining element is the transformer's magnet wire.

217
00:28:02,550 --> 00:28:05,370
I decided to install it perpendicular.

218
00:28:06,790 --> 00:28:14,310
During the build it turned out these inner ribs were in the way.

219
00:28:14,790 --> 00:28:22,290
Because the core height didn't allow full closure.

220
00:28:22,910 --> 00:28:27,210
I cut part of the ribs.

221
00:28:28,790 --> 00:28:31,070
And the core fit nicely.

222
00:28:31,070 --> 00:28:39,510
You can also see a rib was cut opposite the core and top cover.

223
00:28:40,070 --> 00:28:49,850
Here I also made a semicircular cutout for the thermostat semicircle.

224
00:28:50,510 --> 00:28:51,630
It fits here.

225
00:28:52,390 --> 00:28:58,970
After this, we check whether our little enclosure works for mounting at all.

226
00:29:01,310 --> 00:29:02,730
Close it.

227
00:29:04,390 --> 00:29:08,790
The enclosure should fit comfortably.

228
00:29:10,190 --> 00:29:11,890
Now opposite.

229
00:29:13,670 --> 00:29:17,210
And cover our system.

230
00:29:17,330 --> 00:29:24,910
You can see with this mounting our core is solidly fixed.

231
00:29:25,830 --> 00:29:28,110
And there's no shifting.

232
00:29:28,110 --> 00:29:33,610
We'll fix the power module with screws.

233
00:29:34,790 --> 00:29:44,570
I also figured out where the inverter will go for the power side.

234
00:29:46,710 --> 00:29:48,630
Going here.

235
00:29:49,550 --> 00:29:55,230
And I figured out where the control circuit will go.

236
00:29:55,230 --> 00:30:02,590
I decided to install the control scheme perpendicular, in this spot.

237
00:30:02,950 --> 00:30:09,330
To install it I also made a cut in the enclosure rib.

238
00:30:10,750 --> 00:30:13,290
And the board fits in conveniently.

239
00:30:13,510 --> 00:30:22,370
And the main large-size elements are the diode columns.

240
00:30:22,370 --> 00:30:27,310
The diode columns will sit like this, in pairs.

241
00:30:27,510 --> 00:30:32,970
Two pieces on the right and two on the left.

242
00:30:34,070 --> 00:30:44,850
That's how the distribution of all elements ends up in any little enclosure.

243
00:30:45,350 --> 00:30:49,730
This applies to other devices you'll ever make.

244
00:30:49,730 --> 00:30:54,570
You first make the modules, then arrange them conveniently.

245
00:30:54,670 --> 00:31:00,910
And only then conclude whether this enclosure is suitable.

246
00:31:01,910 --> 00:31:06,630
Before installing the control block, you need to test it.

247
00:31:07,910 --> 00:31:11,570
We'll observe oscillograms at these points.

248
00:31:12,670 --> 00:31:15,750
After the 8.2 Ω resistor.

249
00:31:16,450 --> 00:31:19,570
The block isn't yet connected to the power module.

250
00:31:21,730 --> 00:31:30,050
For observing oscillograms, apply 15 V to the control block.

251
00:31:31,290 --> 00:31:33,730
And you see the oscillogram changed.

252
00:31:34,330 --> 00:31:38,230
Now the oscillogram matches the minimum duty cycle.

253
00:31:38,230 --> 00:31:46,450
The driving variable duty cycle resistor is now at its extreme position.

254
00:31:46,990 --> 00:31:58,090
The circuit elements are picked so that at the extreme position duty cycle is 0.7% minimum, but doesn't shut off.

255
00:31:58,930 --> 00:32:05,970
And now you can see that as we rotate the pot, the duty cycle grows.

256
00:32:08,260 --> 00:32:18,720
Now the signal has a maximum duty cycle of 44.4%.

257
00:32:18,720 --> 00:32:26,720
And you can also see we have a pause between control pulses.

258
00:32:27,340 --> 00:32:34,540
The generator works correctly — no channel overlap.

259
00:32:35,540 --> 00:32:47,680
This confirms the driving generator works correctly, the driver works correctly, and the system is built well.

260
00:32:48,380 --> 00:32:54,920
You can also test the switch that disables generation.

261
00:32:54,920 --> 00:33:07,240
Flip the switch and you see that with it turned on, generation stops.

262
00:33:08,440 --> 00:33:14,980
Specifically for pin 3 of the 494 chip.

263
00:33:15,520 --> 00:33:31,160
If you feed in 5 V square signals from another generator here, during the signal itself the chip stops generation.

264
00:33:31,160 --> 00:33:39,360
That way you can do full output modulation of the chip.

265
00:33:40,640 --> 00:33:43,120
May be useful in other devices.

266
00:33:44,040 --> 00:33:46,740
Flip the switch back to the original position.

267
00:33:47,900 --> 00:33:49,340
Generation came back.

268
00:33:50,120 --> 00:33:53,100
Now we can observe the frequency.

269
00:33:53,360 --> 00:33:57,440
Frequency is 16.3 kHz.

270
00:33:57,440 --> 00:34:06,340
That's the minimum frequency set by this resistor.

271
00:34:08,400 --> 00:34:11,340
Now let's see the maximum value.

272
00:34:11,700 --> 00:34:19,400
For this I'll rotate the resistor's control slider with a screwdriver.

273
00:34:24,360 --> 00:34:27,960
You see the frequency growing.

274
00:34:30,340 --> 00:34:32,540
Smooth tuning happens.

275
00:34:34,120 --> 00:34:46,480
And note that throughout the range, as the frequency changes, we don't have signal overlap.

276
00:34:47,440 --> 00:34:51,060
Bringing to maximum.

277
00:34:51,360 --> 00:34:55,440
Now 84 kHz, signal is stable.

278
00:34:57,480 --> 00:34:59,200
Going further.

279
00:35:00,700 --> 00:35:02,380
And bring to maximum.

280
00:35:02,440 --> 00:35:09,100
The maximum corresponds to 253 kHz.

281
00:35:09,100 --> 00:35:25,200
So the 16 to 253 kHz range suits us for tuning any ferrite core to the best frequency response.

282
00:35:25,820 --> 00:35:29,080
Now we can check duty cycle operation.

283
00:35:29,240 --> 00:35:30,960
Also at high frequency.

284
00:35:32,200 --> 00:35:34,280
Minimum and maximum.

285
00:35:34,360 --> 00:35:35,700
Also no overlap.

286
00:35:35,700 --> 00:35:39,720
Meaning the system is built well.

287
00:35:39,880 --> 00:35:44,000
And here we also disable generation with the switch.

288
00:35:46,860 --> 00:35:50,960
That ends the block check.

289
00:35:51,480 --> 00:35:54,840
Can disconnect the probes.

290
00:35:56,140 --> 00:36:00,000
And check one more thing.

291
00:36:00,920 --> 00:36:03,620
The cooler.

292
00:36:04,180 --> 00:36:05,660
Just in case.

293
00:36:07,340 --> 00:36:09,560
Output after the regulator.

294
00:36:10,300 --> 00:36:11,820
Connect the cooler.

295
00:36:14,360 --> 00:36:17,480
You can see it also spins.

296
00:36:17,640 --> 00:36:18,920
Means everything works.

297
00:36:19,060 --> 00:36:20,500
On to the mounting.

298
00:36:22,380 --> 00:36:36,720
After an hour of work, I mounted the control block in the enclosure along with its controls — the DC-DC converter trim pots.

299
00:36:36,940 --> 00:36:43,240
Wired up the main reservoir capacitance and the supply wire.

300
00:36:43,380 --> 00:36:48,960
And the output of the two wires for connecting the power block.

301
00:36:49,460 --> 00:36:52,440
The cooling fan is installed in place.

302
00:36:54,060 --> 00:37:00,040
The whole mount was mainly done with hot glue.

303
00:37:00,040 --> 00:37:06,520
At this moment you can see the DC-DC converter is held by the partition on hot glue.

304
00:37:07,200 --> 00:37:16,300
You can also see the hot glue holds the main cap and the wires.

305
00:37:17,840 --> 00:37:21,460
And in several places the board is fixed.

306
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:28,000
I also applied hot glue on the switch leads so they don't short.

307
00:37:28,000 --> 00:37:36,160
With a metal object — because there's a heat sink nearby.

308
00:37:37,620 --> 00:37:40,040
This is what the back cover looks like.

309
00:37:41,620 --> 00:37:46,260
Generation-disable switch and duty cycle regulation.

310
00:37:46,880 --> 00:37:50,160
Plus and minus power wires.

311
00:37:52,800 --> 00:37:57,080
Now we'll move to mounting the power block.

312
00:37:59,120 --> 00:38:08,700
We'll mount it with two bolts with the press-washers taken from a terminal block.

313
00:38:09,620 --> 00:38:14,380
And I'll show pre-mounting checks for this block.

314
00:38:14,380 --> 00:38:27,860
The power module check is mainly for shorts between the semiconductor power elements and the heat sink.

315
00:38:28,640 --> 00:38:30,920
For this we'll need a multimeter.

316
00:38:31,280 --> 00:38:38,840
Switch it to diode test mode, with audio test.

317
00:38:38,840 --> 00:38:44,300
On a short, the multimeter beeps and shows a short.

318
00:38:44,820 --> 00:38:51,720
Connect one of the test leads to the heat sink.

319
00:38:52,340 --> 00:38:58,040
You see that on contact the multimeter beeps and shows resistance.

320
00:38:59,040 --> 00:39:03,660
And we check the system.

321
00:39:03,660 --> 00:39:13,440
We need that the cooling plate of both transistors isn't shorted to the heat sink.

322
00:39:13,520 --> 00:39:16,300
Check the first transistor.

323
00:39:16,540 --> 00:39:18,080
Check the second transistor.

324
00:39:18,580 --> 00:39:19,360
No beep.

325
00:39:19,860 --> 00:39:24,580
And check all three of its main pins.

326
00:39:24,880 --> 00:39:30,860
Nowhere should we have a short to the body.

327
00:39:30,860 --> 00:39:34,360
The thermostat is also checked.

328
00:39:35,480 --> 00:39:40,060
It also shouldn't short to the body.

329
00:39:42,400 --> 00:39:44,800
Now this block can be mounted.

330
00:39:46,120 --> 00:39:49,960
And one more thermostat check.

331
00:39:50,560 --> 00:39:56,440
But this check is done before mounting it on the heat sink body.

332
00:39:56,440 --> 00:40:04,260
The multimeter stays in test mode for this check.

333
00:40:08,350 --> 00:40:10,450
Put the lead with the alligator clip.

334
00:40:11,310 --> 00:40:25,970
And we see that when the thermostat is cold, it's in the on state for us.

335
00:40:25,970 --> 00:40:29,210
Now we need a heat source.

336
00:40:31,690 --> 00:40:35,030
Heat the surface from some distance.

337
00:40:37,730 --> 00:40:39,710
Thermostat tripped.

338
00:40:40,870 --> 00:40:43,310
The device shows it's open.

339
00:40:44,450 --> 00:40:53,550
After some time when the surface cools, the thermostat should switch back to the on position.

340
00:40:53,550 --> 00:40:55,570
Now wait for cooldown

341
00:41:05,380 --> 00:41:08,500
of the surface.

342
00:41:32,700 --> 00:41:35,380
Hear the beep — thermostat tripped.

343
00:41:36,280 --> 00:41:40,640
It needed about 40 seconds to turn back on.

344
00:41:41,820 --> 00:41:44,100
Since there's no heat sink.

345
00:41:46,220 --> 00:41:50,140
We also check the installed thermostat.

346
00:41:51,140 --> 00:41:57,640
It should show a short.

347
00:41:57,740 --> 00:42:02,240
The system should pass electric current.

348
00:42:03,020 --> 00:42:06,440
That ends the pre-mounting check.

349
00:42:06,920 --> 00:42:19,240
The power module check is mainly for shorts between the semiconductor power elements and the heat sink.

350
00:42:19,240 --> 00:42:22,600
For this we'll need a multimeter.

351
00:42:22,880 --> 00:42:30,540
Switch it to diode test mode, with audio test.

352
00:42:30,780 --> 00:42:35,980
On a short, the multimeter beeps and shows a short.

353
00:42:36,620 --> 00:42:43,380
Connect one of the test leads to the heat sink.

354
00:42:43,380 --> 00:42:49,720
You see that on contact the multimeter beeps and shows resistance.

355
00:42:50,700 --> 00:42:55,340
And we do the system check.

356
00:42:55,800 --> 00:43:05,100
We need that the cooling plate of both transistors isn't shorted to the heat sink.

357
00:43:05,200 --> 00:43:07,980
Check the first transistor.

358
00:43:08,220 --> 00:43:09,760
Check the second transistor.

359
00:43:10,280 --> 00:43:11,040
No beep.

360
00:43:11,040 --> 00:43:16,320
And check all three of its main pins.

361
00:43:16,680 --> 00:43:22,540
Nowhere should we have a short to the body.

362
00:43:23,040 --> 00:43:26,040
The thermostat is also checked.

363
00:43:27,140 --> 00:43:31,740
It also shouldn't short to the body.

364
00:43:34,120 --> 00:43:36,480
Now this block can be mounted.

365
00:43:37,460 --> 00:43:41,660
And one more thermostat check.

366
00:43:42,260 --> 00:43:48,140
But this check is done before mounting it on the heat sink body.

367
00:43:49,820 --> 00:43:55,940
The multimeter stays in test mode for this check.

368
00:44:00,100 --> 00:44:02,120
Put the lead with the alligator clip.

369
00:44:02,120 --> 00:44:17,640
And we see that when the thermostat is cold, it's in the on state for us.

370
00:44:18,400 --> 00:44:20,860
Now we need a heat source.

371
00:44:23,260 --> 00:44:26,640
Heat the surface from some distance.

372
00:44:29,300 --> 00:44:31,380
Thermostat tripped.

373
00:44:32,380 --> 00:44:35,020
The device shows it's open.

374
00:44:36,060 --> 00:44:45,240
After some time when the surface cools, the thermostat should switch back to the on position.

375
00:44:45,680 --> 00:44:47,240
Now wait for cooldown.

376
00:44:50,120 --> 00:44:53,080
Hear the beep — thermostat tripped.

377
00:44:54,000 --> 00:44:58,320
It needed about 40 seconds to turn back on.

378
00:44:59,260 --> 00:45:01,800
Since there's no heat sink.

379
00:45:03,800 --> 00:45:07,840
We also check the installed thermostat.

380
00:45:09,820 --> 00:45:15,340
It should show a short.

381
00:45:15,440 --> 00:45:19,940
The system should pass electric current.

382
00:45:20,700 --> 00:45:24,160
That ends the pre-mounting check.

383
00:45:24,160 --> 00:45:27,620
Did the power module mounting.

384
00:45:28,080 --> 00:45:35,420
Connected the supply wires and connected the gates to the drivers.

385
00:45:36,120 --> 00:45:37,820
Here you see two wires.

386
00:45:38,600 --> 00:45:42,820
Now we need to test overall system operation.

387
00:45:43,260 --> 00:45:50,140
For this we'll need a 12 V, 21 W lamp.

388
00:45:50,140 --> 00:45:55,040
Connect it at this point.

389
00:45:56,860 --> 00:46:01,260
Here, to our thermostat.

390
00:46:02,280 --> 00:46:08,080
And the second end of the lamp goes alternately to the power switch drains.

391
00:46:08,840 --> 00:46:15,540
These are the points corresponding to where the future primary windings will connect.

392
00:46:16,540 --> 00:46:22,880
For this we need to feed supply voltage.

393
00:46:25,940 --> 00:46:28,660
I applied voltage.

394
00:46:29,000 --> 00:46:33,480
You can see the cooler is running.

395
00:46:34,680 --> 00:46:35,880
And we connect the lamp.

396
00:46:36,020 --> 00:46:43,140
The system's duty cycle control is now set to minimum.

397
00:46:45,600 --> 00:46:48,180
You see the lamp doesn't light up.

398
00:46:48,260 --> 00:46:49,940
Now I add duty cycle.

399
00:46:54,260 --> 00:47:01,020
And you see the lamp warms up — regulation works.

400
00:47:04,850 --> 00:47:08,810
We can also check the switch for disabling generation.

401
00:47:10,070 --> 00:47:14,010
Generation off, generation on.

402
00:47:15,010 --> 00:47:19,230
The second power switch is checked the same way.

403
00:47:20,730 --> 00:47:24,470
Connect to the drain and check.

404
00:47:28,910 --> 00:47:36,710
The glow regulates and generation turns off and on.

405
00:47:38,390 --> 00:47:43,750
Lamp glow regulation confirms full operability.

406
00:47:43,750 --> 00:47:52,970
The most labor-intensive and critical part of our device is the secondary winding of the high-voltage transformer.

407
00:47:54,010 --> 00:48:01,030
I wound it with 0.4 mm lacquered wire.

408
00:48:02,030 --> 00:48:09,050
When I bought this core, no winding form came in the kit.

409
00:48:09,230 --> 00:48:14,830
And I made one from transparent plastic from packaging.

410
00:48:15,490 --> 00:48:22,170
I cut a strip to size and glued two layers together with super glue.

411
00:48:23,550 --> 00:48:29,950
Got this build — as you can see, it's rigid and holds well.

412
00:48:29,950 --> 00:48:32,110
As for the winding.

413
00:48:32,650 --> 00:48:45,110
I managed to lay 22 layers of 40 turns before filling the inside of the core surface.

414
00:48:46,850 --> 00:48:53,030
Inter-layer insulation I did with electrical tape 30 mm wide.

415
00:48:53,030 --> 00:49:07,230
Let me show how to do the insulation using the example of a winding I made for a round TVS core.

416
00:49:07,930 --> 00:49:15,030
Lay the wire turn-to-turn, carefully filling the space.

417
00:49:16,530 --> 00:49:22,490
Once a layer is wound, electrical tape is applied on top.

418
00:49:23,030 --> 00:49:30,670
And the wire that transitions to the next layer is pulled up onto the tape surface.

419
00:49:31,770 --> 00:49:36,510
After that, it's held and the gluing happens.

420
00:49:37,070 --> 00:49:48,910
With a tight fit, you can see the tape extends about a centimeter beyond the surface.

421
00:49:48,910 --> 00:49:56,550
We have the protrusion under the tape from the previous layer's wire.

422
00:49:56,650 --> 00:50:04,230
After that the wire wraps around and lays the next layer past this protrusion.

423
00:50:06,630 --> 00:50:11,010
The winding goes on with tension and we have the next layer.

424
00:50:11,150 --> 00:50:17,270
This way we gradually build our winding.

425
00:50:18,270 --> 00:50:27,290
What's worth noting is that the tape should extend much wider than the layer itself.

426
00:50:27,710 --> 00:50:34,530
Because the voltage between turns in a layer isn't that big.

427
00:50:34,630 --> 00:50:39,910
It might be from tens to a few tens of volts.

428
00:50:39,910 --> 00:50:44,170
And the voltage between layers is much more significant.

429
00:50:45,130 --> 00:50:48,830
It can reach several hundred volts between each layer.

430
00:50:48,930 --> 00:50:59,770
So the insulation should extend at least half a centimeter beyond the layer width on each side.

431
00:51:00,250 --> 00:51:03,210
This prevents inter-layer breakdown.

432
00:51:04,370 --> 00:51:08,970
That's the requirement for winding high-voltage windings.

433
00:51:08,970 --> 00:51:14,770
Because what we need to prevent is inter-layer shorting, not inter-turn shorting.

434
00:51:16,170 --> 00:51:23,350
I've already checked many such windings in operation on different cores.

435
00:51:23,530 --> 00:51:27,370
And this method has proven itself very well.

436
00:51:28,150 --> 00:51:35,710
I don't recommend using a regular TVS winding as the secondary.

437
00:51:35,710 --> 00:51:41,550
Because there are many turns and the wire is thin.

438
00:51:42,450 --> 00:51:50,590
I'm building this high-voltage power block for good current.

439
00:51:51,310 --> 00:51:54,710
So the wire cross-section should be thicker.

440
00:51:55,470 --> 00:52:01,470
Good secondary winding current will let us run quality experiments with spark gaps.

441
00:52:01,470 --> 00:52:08,450
Because the current that charges the capacitor matters in these experiments.

442
00:52:09,110 --> 00:52:15,630
And such wire holds a good load under short circuit.

443
00:52:16,430 --> 00:52:21,710
It doesn't burn inside the layer.

444
00:52:23,370 --> 00:52:27,970
Making this secondary winding took me about three hours.

445
00:52:27,970 --> 00:52:31,450
Here's how it sits on the core.

446
00:52:32,170 --> 00:52:35,830
And now we can move to making the primary winding.

447
00:52:36,550 --> 00:52:42,670
For this we'll need to buy two heat-shrink tubes of minimum diameter.

448
00:52:43,370 --> 00:52:48,470
And wire with an outer cross-section over the lacquer of 0.8 mm.

449
00:52:48,990 --> 00:52:55,470
From this wire, a piece 4 m 20 cm long is cut and folded in half.

450
00:52:55,470 --> 00:52:59,790
You get a double wire 2 m 10 cm long.

451
00:53:00,250 --> 00:53:04,950
After that the double wire is twisted into a braid with a drill or screwdriver.

452
00:53:05,570 --> 00:53:08,290
And heat shrink is applied over it.

453
00:53:09,310 --> 00:53:15,610
It gets baked and you get quality wire for the primary winding.

454
00:53:16,070 --> 00:53:19,950
After twisting you get this nice braid.

455
00:53:20,770 --> 00:53:25,050
To make this easier and do it alone, you'll need a screwdriver.

456
00:53:25,430 --> 00:53:27,650
Clamp the second end on it.

457
00:53:28,390 --> 00:53:32,930
Put your foot down, and pull the wire up with the screwdriver.

458
00:53:33,270 --> 00:53:35,150
And start twisting.

459
00:53:36,150 --> 00:53:41,730
Thread the central ring on an auxiliary wire tool.

460
00:53:42,570 --> 00:53:43,370
And twist.

461
00:53:44,300 --> 00:53:49,790
You can see I've already put one half of the wire in heat shrink.

462
00:53:50,430 --> 00:53:58,270
Leave some distance here for the plus electrode to be soldered.

463
00:54:00,230 --> 00:54:04,650
Here it is — this wire on the schematic, the central point.

464
00:54:05,570 --> 00:54:14,290
And before laying the wire in heat shrink, the tip needs to be either soldered or smoothed nicely.

465
00:54:14,450 --> 00:54:18,390
Then the heat shrink goes on without issues.

466
00:54:18,710 --> 00:54:24,250
If there are protrusions, you risk tearing it or struggling for a long time.

467
00:54:24,430 --> 00:54:27,090
It lays in really easily.

468
00:54:28,710 --> 00:54:33,350
You can see the wire pulls through without effort.

469
00:54:46,670 --> 00:54:55,830
That's it — now we can also heat-treat the second side.

470
00:54:56,710 --> 00:55:00,850
And we can move to winding the primary.

471
00:55:01,750 --> 00:55:12,790
Before laying the wire on the transformer core, carefully clean the wire's central point of lacquer insulation with a sharp object.

472
00:55:13,290 --> 00:55:15,910
Clean and solder.

473
00:55:18,750 --> 00:55:26,190
Before starting the primary winding, the wire needs to be formed — give it shape.

474
00:55:26,810 --> 00:55:36,150
Make a lead long enough to reach the plus electrode of the thermostat terminal.

475
00:55:37,210 --> 00:55:41,910
After this, pull one of the wires through the core.

476
00:55:43,750 --> 00:55:47,190
The second goes in the direction of the opposite side.

477
00:55:47,190 --> 00:56:01,570
To know that the primary is wound correctly — if leading it on winding from the center, you need to wind both halves counter to each other.

478
00:56:02,070 --> 00:56:08,090
That is, we push the wire from one half in

479
00:56:11,470 --> 00:56:14,670
one direction and make a crossing.

480
00:56:14,670 --> 00:56:16,930
That's the next layer.

481
00:56:17,130 --> 00:56:24,550
And push the second end of the wire counter-wise and pull.

482
00:56:24,710 --> 00:56:31,990
This forms a winding with wire crossings.

483
00:56:32,850 --> 00:56:43,110
And every time we alternate crossings, the wire ends stay the same length.

484
00:56:50,660 --> 00:57:01,260
We've already gone the eighth turn of each wire.

485
00:57:02,180 --> 00:57:07,420
That gives us 8 turns per arm now.

486
00:57:15,410 --> 00:57:26,390
Try to pull the wire carefully so it doesn't pass too tightly.

487
00:57:26,530 --> 00:57:32,230
Rubbing its heat shrink against sharp ferrite edges.

488
00:57:33,610 --> 00:57:39,370
Wire formed by a braid is very convenient to work with.

489
00:57:39,530 --> 00:57:45,870
It's soft, bends in all directions, and clearly holds its shape.

490
00:57:46,390 --> 00:57:54,330
Drop it — it doesn't unravel, unlike single-strand wound wire.

491
00:58:03,370 --> 00:58:14,730
The turn count per arm in the primary winding ultimately determines the converter's consumption.

492
00:58:18,350 --> 00:58:23,470
You also regulate output power with the turn count.

493
00:58:23,470 --> 00:58:37,010
There's an approximate rule that you want about 2 volts per turn.

494
00:58:38,910 --> 00:58:44,710
This rule is worth following but is somewhat conditional.

495
00:58:44,850 --> 00:58:51,890
You can go to 1.5 volts per turn — I mean the supply voltage.

496
00:58:51,890 --> 00:59:03,570
For example, if you power the primary with 12 V, about 6 turns is roughly enough.

497
00:59:04,230 --> 00:59:11,250
That gives us 2 volts per turn of the primary winding.

498
00:59:12,250 --> 00:59:15,550
That value can vary.

499
00:59:16,550 --> 00:59:22,570
We'll do a test winding of 10 turns now.

500
00:59:26,250 --> 00:59:34,230
Finished winding the primary and connected the high-voltage transformer in the circuit.

501
00:59:34,230 --> 00:59:42,610
Got 10 turns per arm — that is, 10 turns connected to each transistor.

502
00:59:43,630 --> 00:59:50,670
And the high-voltage transformer is now connected to this kind of spark gap.

503
00:59:50,670 --> 00:59:55,690
The spark gap wire is 1.5 mm copper.

504
00:59:57,150 --> 01:00:06,730
The shape is this because the wire heats up very strongly and melting happens.

505
01:00:07,230 --> 01:00:14,930
So the length should be big so the solder contacts don't melt.

506
01:00:16,650 --> 01:00:21,490
We'll start from a lab power source.

507
01:00:22,130 --> 01:00:28,410
We'll apply 13 V to the input — the system isn't connected yet.

508
01:00:29,690 --> 01:00:43,730
Before starting, you need to set the duty cycle to minimum and disconnect the cooler's power terminal.

509
01:00:43,730 --> 01:00:45,250
Here it's disconnected.

510
01:00:45,610 --> 01:00:50,550
To exclude its effect on consumption current.

511
01:00:52,130 --> 01:00:56,530
Plus wire connected, connect minus.

512
01:01:00,950 --> 01:01:05,290
System is at minimum duty cycle now.

513
01:01:08,990 --> 01:01:14,090
Consumption — you see, 0.03 A, 13 V.

514
01:01:14,880 --> 01:01:24,650
And now we'll add duty cycle until the discharge ignites.

515
01:01:24,910 --> 01:01:32,690
Cranked the duty cycle to max — we get 0.09 A at 13 V.

516
01:01:32,690 --> 01:01:41,970
In this position when the discharge isn't burning, we need to tune the generator frequency.

517
01:01:43,250 --> 01:01:56,370
Tune with the trim pot to the minimum consumption at maximum duty cycle until the discharge ignites.

518
01:01:57,830 --> 01:02:01,690
That ends the frequency tuning.

519
01:02:02,690 --> 01:02:10,270
After that, we can still make small corrections while watching the discharge burn.

520
01:02:10,830 --> 01:02:24,130
On the contrary — when the discharge crosses the spark gap, we now have alternating voltage, and consumption should be at maximum.

521
01:02:25,130 --> 01:02:38,820
Now I'll connect the wire so we get a breakdown.

522
01:02:40,680 --> 01:02:47,680
You see the consumption is now 4.4 A.

523
01:02:48,880 --> 01:02:53,840
And we need to tune it to maximum by adjusting the frequency.

524
01:02:53,840 --> 01:03:08,040
You want to reach the moment when the wire in the spark gap melts — that is, it heats up.

525
01:03:09,820 --> 01:03:12,860
The camera is slightly out of focus.

526
01:03:13,320 --> 01:03:17,220
Now I'll try with a white sheet in the background.

527
01:03:31,430 --> 01:03:41,630
The discharge from a 13 V supply can stretch 4–5 mm.

528
01:03:44,350 --> 01:03:53,050
Stable discharge ignition from about a 2 mm distance.

529
01:03:53,050 --> 01:04:01,270
The output voltage is low, but the current is pretty powerful.

530
01:04:01,670 --> 01:04:09,530
This is what you want from a high-voltage generator like this.

531
01:04:09,530 --> 01:04:21,650
For our experiments, voltage from 1.5 to 3 kW is more suitable.

532
01:04:22,390 --> 01:04:24,990
So you don't need to push the voltage too high.

533
01:04:25,310 --> 01:04:38,930
But for those interested in higher voltage, wind more turns on the secondary and decrease the turn count on the primary.

534
01:04:39,530 --> 01:04:55,010
Then you can get the discharges we see in videos online, where people stretch 4–8 cm discharges.

535
01:04:55,310 --> 01:04:57,010
That's how you get there.

536
01:04:57,770 --> 01:05:00,330
For practical use, not needed.

537
01:05:04,350 --> 01:05:18,330
If you'll operate this high-voltage generator predominantly at 12 V, I recommend reducing the turn count from 10 to 8.

538
01:05:18,650 --> 01:05:26,910
Then the melting will be most intense and the copper will drip down.

539
01:05:26,910 --> 01:05:38,310
For me, 10 turns on the primary works because I plan to operate this generator up to 36 V input.

540
01:05:38,310 --> 01:05:52,590
You can see the discharge breaks down about 1 mm — the voltage isn't that high but the current is very powerful.

541
01:05:54,270 --> 01:05:57,730
Can melt nails — steel melts well.

542
01:06:01,050 --> 01:06:05,030
You can also look at the regulation.

543
01:06:05,070 --> 01:06:09,210
I lower the duty cycle now.

544
01:06:09,850 --> 01:06:14,110
You see the discharge intensity decreases.

545
01:06:16,570 --> 01:06:18,010
Added it back.

546
01:06:19,070 --> 01:06:23,730
You see the metal is red-hot, and on contact the wires solder together.

547
01:06:24,730 --> 01:06:39,730
At full short circuit nothing happens — the system's out-of-order consumption drops.

548
01:06:42,310 --> 01:06:44,390
Now it holds stably.

549
01:06:45,390 --> 01:06:49,970
The converter runs in short-circuit mode.

550
01:06:52,090 --> 01:07:03,490
And the heat sink has a temperature of about 40°C without airflow.

551
01:07:04,490 --> 01:07:07,430
In short-circuit mode.

552
01:07:09,410 --> 01:07:19,850
Now we can move to installing the diode columns and finishing the build.

553
01:07:21,430 --> 01:07:41,050
Before final mounting, glue the core on all sides, wrap it tightly with electrical tape, glue the winding from both sides, and fix the wires.

554
01:07:41,890 --> 01:07:53,090
Also bend the leads that go to the transistor pins into a ring shape for solid soldering.

555
01:07:59,440 --> 01:08:01,680
Device assembly is nearly done.

556
01:08:02,500 --> 01:08:07,760
Installed the front panel — you can see the negative and positive terminals.

557
01:08:07,760 --> 01:08:12,880
Installed the diode columns, mostly held with hot glue.

558
01:08:15,980 --> 01:08:29,960
Connected the diode column inputs per the schematic — these are the points where the high-voltage winding of the step-up transformer will connect.

559
01:08:29,960 --> 01:08:38,160
Now I'll install the transformer and we can move to full device tests.

560
01:08:40,960 --> 01:08:44,940
All mounted — that's the build we ended up with.

561
01:08:45,940 --> 01:08:53,720
If it's made for voltage up to 5 kW, the centimeter gaps between contacts are quite enough.

562
01:08:53,840 --> 01:09:03,600
If more, you'd need a bigger enclosure and to keep distance between the diode columns and between the terminals themselves.

563
01:09:04,920 --> 01:09:08,540
Up to 5 kW, this build is pretty reliable.

564
01:09:15,390 --> 01:09:18,730
Holding the transformer — it's not fixed yet.

565
01:09:19,590 --> 01:09:24,170
The top cover will press it down solidly.

566
01:09:32,300 --> 01:09:39,240
Instead of feet, I put soft rubber here on the screws.

567
01:10:21,010 --> 01:10:22,130
That's it.

568
01:10:23,430 --> 01:10:27,710
Such a little box — nothing rattles.

569
01:10:28,430 --> 01:10:30,830
All pretty solid.

570
01:10:31,650 --> 01:10:45,630
And these feet provide the exact air gap below so the cooler can draw air for system cooling.

571
01:10:49,910 --> 01:10:58,690
Now we'll run an experiment that clearly shows the difference between AC discharge and DC discharge.

572
01:10:58,690 --> 01:11:06,750
The right spark gap electrode is connected to the positive terminal, the left to negative.

573
01:11:07,590 --> 01:11:12,150
The device will be powered with 13 V.

574
01:11:12,770 --> 01:11:19,970
And we'll observe melting of the negative electrode with the device's overall consumption at 4 A.

575
01:11:20,590 --> 01:11:26,070
Electrode cross-section is 1.5 mm in diameter.

576
01:11:27,070 --> 01:11:29,130
Turn on the device.

577
01:11:32,170 --> 01:11:34,730
Now I'll ignite the discharge.

578
01:11:36,890 --> 01:11:38,390
The electrodes stick together.

579
01:11:44,070 --> 01:11:47,390
That's DC — electricity literally attracts.

580
01:11:50,070 --> 01:11:51,690
Electrode to electrode.

581
01:12:01,280 --> 01:12:02,740
Welding happens.

582
01:12:07,460 --> 01:12:09,080
Process started.

583
01:12:12,320 --> 01:12:17,900
You see the negative electrode melting.
